To synthesize SANs, 2 g (2 % w/v) of CMC was first added to 100 mL of deionized water and stirred using a magnetic stirrer for 3 h to create a homogeneous solution. Then 2 g (2 % w/v) of SPA was added to the solution and stirred for 30 min to obtain a homogeneous and high-viscosity gel solution for preparing samples. Finally, the solution was divided into 4 equal parts. The first part was used to synthesize the first sample (CMC-SPA). In the second part, 5 % w/v of CDs synthesized by pyrolysis method, which was previously powdered by ball mill, was added and stirred at room temperature at 500 rpm for 30 min (CMC-SPA-CD). Also, 2 % v/v SEO was added to the third part and stirred at 500 rpm for 30 min (CMC-SPA-SEO). Finally, 5 % w/v CDs and 2 % v/v SEO were added to the fourth part (CMC-SPA-CD-SEO). To complete the synthesis, the samples were poured into separate Petri dishes and freeze-dried for 24 h (
                        Fig. 1
                        ).

The results of the mechanical properties of the four samples showed that the addition of CDs and SEO had significant effects on the tensile strength, bending stress, and elongation at break of the samples (
                        Fig. 4
                        ). The tensile strength of the samples increased with the addition of CD but decreased with the addition of SEO. The highest tensile strength was observed for the CMC/SPA/CD sample (4.6 MPa), which was more than twice as high as the CMC/SPA sample (2.1 MPa). The lowest tensile strength was observed for the CMC/SPA/SEO sample (2.7 MPa), which was slightly higher than the CMC/SPA sample. The CMC/SPA/CD/SEO sample had a moderate tensile strength of 3.5 MPa, indicating that the presence of SEO reduced the positive effect of CDs on the tensile strength. The bending stress of the samples increased with both CDs and SEO, but the effect of SEO was more pronounced. The highest bending stress was observed for the CMC/SPA/CD/SEO sample (54.8 MPa), which was almost 70 % higher than the CMC/SPA sample (32.5 MPa). The lowest bending stress was observed for the CMC/SPA sample, which was followed by the CMC/SPA/CD sample (43.5 MPa). The CMC/SPA/SEO sample had a high bending stress of 37.6 MPa, indicating that SEO improved the flexibility of the nanocomposite. The elongation at break of the samples showed a complex pattern with respect to CDs and SEO. The highest elongation at break was observed for the CMC/SPA/SEO sample (43.7 %), which was more than 60 % higher than the CMC/SPA sample (27.2 %). The lowest elongation at break was observed for the CMC/SPA/CD sample (18.3 %), which was almost 33 % lower than the CMC/SPA sample. The CMC/SPA/CD/SEO sample had a moderate elongation at break of 22.2 %, indicating that SEO partially compensated for the negative effect of CDs on the ductility of the nanocomposite. The results suggest that CDs and SEO have different roles in enhancing the mechanical properties of the superabsorbent nanocomposite samples. CDs can increase the tensile strength by forming cross-links between CMC and SPA chains but also decrease the elongation at break by reducing the chain mobility [32]. SEO can increase the bending stress and elongation at break by acting as a plasticizer and reducing the intermolecular interactions between CMC and SPA chains but also decrease the tensile strength by weakening the cross-links formed by CDs [33]. Therefore, an optimal balance between CDs and SEO content is needed to achieve a high-performance superabsorbent nanocomposite with desirable mechanical properties.

The absorption rate of the four samples was measured at different pH and ionic concentrations (

                        Fig. 5
                        ). The results showed that the sample containing CMC, SPA, and CDs synthesized by the pyrolysis method (CMC/SPA/CD) had the highest water absorption capacity (8621 %) among all the samples. The CMC/SPA/SEO sample had the lowest absorption capacity (6818 %). The absorption rate of the samples decreased as the pH and ionic concentration of the solution increased. The CMC/SPA/CD/SEO sample had a moderate absorption capacity (7528 %) compared to the other samples. The sample containing CMC and SPA (CMC/SPA) had a water absorption capacity of 8100 %. The HCl absorption of the samples was as follows: CMC/SPA (1862 %), CMC/SPA/CD (1955 %), CMC/SPA/SEO (1735 %), and CMC/SPA/CD/SEO (1808 %). The NaOH absorption of the samples was as follows: CMC/SPA (1697 %), CMC/SPA/CD (1794 %), CMC/SPA/SEO (1530 %), and CMC/SPA/CD/SEO (1636 %). The NaCl absorption of the samples at different concentrations was as follows: CMC/SPA (4202 % at 0.1 M, 3796 % at 0.5 M and 3367 % at 1 M), CMC/SPA/CD (4377 % at 0.1 M, 3908 % at 0.5 M and 3536 % at 1 M), CMC/SPA/SEO (3543 % at 0.1 M, 3146 % at 0.5 M and 2831 % at 1 M) and CMC/SPA/CD/SEO (4063 % at 0.1 M, 3596 % at 0.5 M and 3154 % at 1 M). The high-water absorption capacity of CMC/SPA/CD can be attributed to the positive effect of the three components. CMC is a hydrophilic polymer that can form hydrogen bonds with water molecules and swell in aqueous solutions [34]. SPA is a super absorbent polymer that can absorb water through its carboxylate groups and form a three-dimensional network structure [9]. CDs are nanomaterials that have high surface area, porosity, and functional groups that can interact with water molecules and enhance the water retention of the composite [35]. The pyrolysis method used to synthesize CDs can also increase their crystallinity and stability, which can improve their performance as a water absorbent [36]. The low water absorption capacity of CMC/SPA/SEO can be explained by the possible interference of SEO with the swelling mechanism of CMC and SPA [25]. However, it may also reduce the hydrophilicity and solubility of CMC and SPA by forming hydrophobic interactions or cross-linking bonds with them. Moreover, SEO may evaporate or leach out from the composite during the swelling process, which can decrease its water retention ability [37]. The moderate water absorption capacity of CMC/SPA/CD/SEO can be attributed to the balance between the positive effect of CDs and the negative effect of SEO on the swelling behavior of CMC and SPA. CDs may enhance the water absorption of CMC and SPA by providing additional sites for water molecules to bind and increasing the porosity and stability of the composite [38]. SEO may reduce the water absorption of CMC and SPA by decreasing their hydrophilicity and solubility and causing volatilization or leaching losses. Therefore, the optimal ratio of CDs and SEO in the composite should be determined to achieve the maximum water absorption capacity. The decrease in water absorption of the samples as the pH and ionic concentration of the solution increased can be attributed to the ionization and salting-out effects [39]. As the pH of the solution decreased, more carboxylate groups in CMC and SPA became protonated and lost their ability to bind water molecules [40]. As the pH of the solution increased, more hydroxide ions competed with water molecules for binding sites on CMC and SPA, which reduced their swelling degree. The combination of CDs and SEO resulted in a trade-off between the nanocomposite's absorption and swelling properties, depending on the ratio and interaction of the two components. The results suggest that the water absorption of the superabsorbent nanocomposites can be tuned by varying the composition and ratio of the components. The water absorption behavior of the nanocomposites can be explained by considering the molecular structure, chemical bonding, and physical characteristics of the components, as well as their interfacial interactions. These findings suggest that CDs can be used as an effective additive to enhance the performance of superabsorbent nanocomposites.
